Real wage growth needs more productive workers
Britain's poor productivity must be tackled if 2014 is to become the year that pay rises catch up with price increases, according to the Chartered Institute of Personnel and Development (CIPD).
Employment growth looks set to continue through 2014, with even upwards-revised Office for Budget Responsibility forecasts of increases in employment and falls in unemployment looking conservative, Mr Beatson said. Photo: Rex	By Alan Tovey
3:29PM GMT 01 Jan 2014
Follow Comments
Britain's poor productivity must be tackled if 2014 is to become the year that pay rises catch up with price increases, according to the Chartered Institute of Personnel and Development (CIPD).
Mark Beatson, chief economist at the human resources organisation, said that while what he termed the country’s “enigma” of strong job creation despite muted economic performance has now been solved with recent strong economic growth, a new challenge faces industry in the form of low productivity.
“This time last year we were talking about the UK’s 'jobs enigma’. Since then, labour market performance has continued to exceed expectations, turning the UK labour market into a 'jobs machine’.
“Employment growth looks set to continue at an impressive rate over the year to come. However, the downside is that UK productivity has yet to improve and remains below its pre-recession level.”
Employment growth looks set to continue through 2014, with even upwards-revised Office for Budget Responsibility forecasts of increases in employment and falls in unemployment looking conservative, Mr Beatson said.
