Equitable Life compensation payments to begin
Investors who lost money with Equitable Life are to start receiving compensation next month, the Government has announced. The Equitable Life compensation scheme will aim to contact all eligible policyholders before June 2012 By Richard Evans
1:54PM BST 16 May 2011
Follow Comments
Older policyholders, those receiving with-profits annuities and the estates of victims who have died will be given priority. Of these groups, only the annuitants will be compensated in full – payments to the other investors will amount to less than a quarter of the amount lost. In all, Equitable Life victims will receive about £1.5bn. Mark Hoban, the financial secretary to the Treasury, said the compensation scheme had been designed to reflect "the principles of fairness, transparency and simplicity". The scheme will aim to contact all eligible policyholders before June 2012, regardless of whether they will receive a payment. Policyholders will be sent a statement explaining the value of any payment and details on when they can expect to receive it. The compensation, which is tax-free, will not be means-tested and will not affect eligibility for tax credits, but could be taken into account when other state benefits are calculated. Anyone reckoned to be eligible for compensation of less than £10 will not receive a payment. Related Articles
Cameron deal on Equitable 'a slap in the face'
26 Jan 2011
Equitable redress: just £266
23 Jul 2010
Equitable boosts members' policy values
04 Jan 2010
Equitable Life: Government finally says 'sorry' to policyholders
16 Jan 2009
The Treasury said payments could be brought forward on the grounds of hardship "regardless of circumstances". Mr Hoban added: "Having spent a great deal of time in dialogue with interested parties, the Government is now approaching the final stages of preparation before the [compensation] scheme begins to make payments to policyholders. "The Government's ambition is for these payments to begin before the end of June."
National Savings & Investments (NS&I), the Government's savings arm, is to administer the scheme. Policyholders do not need to take action at this stage, the Treasury said. The Equitable Members' Action Group expressed "outrage" at what it called "payment delays". "A million victims will be in the dark for yet another year," it said. Featured Isa / Investment platforms »
