Poll shows more support for abandoning gay marriage plans rather than plain packaging
The Government has come under further pressure to drop its gay marriage plans after a new poll showed more people wanted them scrapped than the scheme to ensure cigarettes are sold in plain packaging, which was recently kicked into the long grass. Gay marriage is set to become law after clearing the House of Lords. Photo: ALAMY	6:47AM BST 08 May 2013
Ministers have recently cooled on the proposals to force tobacco firms to sell their products in such packets and the plans are unlikely to feature in this week's Queen’s Speech. However, the Government has indicated it will continue with its same sex marriage legislation. The ComRes poll, for the Coalition For Marriage (C4M), the campaign group set up to oppose the proposals, involved asking 2,000 adults which of the two policies they would prefer to see abandoned. Just over a third (34 per cent) opted for gay marriage, compared with 28 per cent, who wanted plain packaging plans scrapped. The remainder opted for “neither” or said they did not know. Among those who voted Conservative at the last general election, 46 per cent wanted same sex marriage legislation dropped, compared with 22 per cent who would rather see the tobacco plans abandoned. Related Articles
RSPCA 'wasted court time' with hunting case
07 May 2013
Gay marriage will haunt Cameron
10 May 2013
No apology from Downing Street over Dalai Lama meeting
07 May 2013
Lord Carey tells Cameron: stop treating grassroots like 'dinosaurs'
09 May 2013
Colin Hart, campaign director for C4M, said: “This poll yet again shows how out of touch David Cameron is with his own party and the public at large. “The Prime Minister still remains determined to force through this undemocratic and unpopular legislation, which has never been voted upon by the electorate and which contributed to the disastrous local election results. “Poll after poll has found that this issue could cost the Conservatives more than a million votes and the next general election.”
The plain packaging proposals were first outlined by Andrew Lansley, the former Health Secretary, last year. Health campaigners argue it would discourage young people from taking up smoking. The Government’s consultation on plain packaging closed in August, but it is yet to publish a report on it. It is now understood the policy has been kicked into the long grass, although a Department of Health spokesman insisted that the Government maintained an “open mind” on the issue. Politics
