Worldwide: Harassed women fight back in groper's paradise
By Philip Delves Broughton in Rabat
12:01AM BST 17 Aug 2002
Morocco's street-side predators, like Kentucky's Colonel Sanders, are mostly leg and thigh men. A woman in a tight T-shirt will attract double takes and murmurs, but a short skirt and flash of leg will prompt pursuit, indecent proposals and often a furtive squeeze. You would have thought that an ambitious country, keen to attract tourists, would be doing something about its reputation as a groper's paradise. But no. On the basis of two hours in Rabat's Old City and conversations with Moroccan women and tourists, Moroccan men remain as persistent as ever, wolf-whistling, bottom-pinching and goatishly profferring themselves to passing women. They will often just sidle up and start whispering dirty nothings in their target's ear until she runs away. It is a fact of life mentioned in every guide book and an embarrassment for a country so desperate to be taken seriously in the world. The bottom-squeezers are to Morocco what football hooligans have been to Britain. For Moroccan women it is just as much of a problem as it is for tourists passing through Agadir in their holiday crop tops. Laws exist to punish men for sexual harassment, but they are tilted heavily against the victim, who must provide photographs or at least two witnesses to the incident. The high burden of proof dissuades many women from complaining.
Related Articles
Moroccan playboy king weds
24 Mar 2002
Policemen often stand by laughing while their friends bay like coyotes at a woman walking by. They see it perhaps as part of the great pageant of street life which, if you are a randy young Moroccan man, of course it is. The reasons for Morocco's failure to stop it are the same as those hindering the country from development on other fronts. It has yet to find a way to reconcile its desire for modernity with Islamic tradition, which as interpreted by Morocco's vocal fundamentalists sees improving rights for women as an affront to men. Lamia Bouzbouz, a journalist for Liberation, a newspaper representing the majority party in the current government, has been among those pleading for change. "Sexual harassment has become a fun little game for many men, a practice so common in our daily life that it has become banal," she wrote recently. "I decided to write this because I have been a victim so often myself," she said from her office in Casablanca. "The level of proof a woman needs is insulting, and it becomes even more serious when the abuse turns physical." But she does not predict any change for at least 10 years. Unlike women in many other Islamic countries, Morocco's are well organised. There are dozens of women's groups. They are learning how to put pressure on the government and the king. In next month's legislative elections, the king has ruled, 10 per cent of those elected must be women. Mohammed VI, 34, is proving more considerate to women than his father, King Hassan II. His marriage last month was remarkable in that his wife appeared in public, a break from the tradition under which wives stay firmly in the shadows. He also seems determined to heed calls for changes to the Moudawana, a body of marriage and property law drafted in 1957 after Moroccan independence, which mixes local tradition and Islamic Sharia law. It is hugely disadvantageous to women and empowering for men. It dictates that all women need permission from a male guardian to marry. It limits their ability to leave their husbands, gives them almost no property rights or access to their children if their husband decides to divorce, and turns them essentially into marital slaves. A government committee was appointed in 1999 to examine changes to the Moudawana, including granting the first wife the right of veto over her husband taking more wives, raising the legal age of marriage from 15 to 18 and making judges the final arbiters in divorces. But street protests by fundamentalists rocked the government back, forcing the king to put together his own committee, which has yet to report. Morocco
